      { name: "Donepezil", type: "Cholinesterase Inhibitor", action: "Reversibly inhibits acetylcholinesterase, increasing acetylcholine availability at cholinergic synapses in the cortex and hippocampus. Approved for mild, moderate, and severe Alzheimer's disease. Start 5 mg daily × 4-6 weeks then increase to 10 mg daily. 23 mg formulation available for moderate-severe disease.", sideEffects: "Nausea, diarrhea, insomnia, vivid dreams, muscle cramps, bradycardia, syncope", contra: "Sick sinus syndrome without pacemaker, active GI bleeding, severe hepatic impairment", pearl: "Take donepezil at BEDTIME to minimize GI side effects (nausea/diarrhea). If nightmares/insomnia occur, switch to morning dosing. Monitor heart rate — can cause clinically significant bradycardia, especially with concurrent beta-blockers or calcium channel blockers. The 23 mg dose has significantly more GI side effects than the 10 mg dose." }
